			<h2>Etiquette</h2>
			<p>As a PGA Professional I receive a lot of questions from new golfers about how to act or behave when they are out on the golf course. I think that new golfers tend to ask these types of questions for fear of doing something wrong as being on the course is an unknown for them. So I always start when explaining etiquette with what etiquette means. The definition of etiquette is&hellip; The practices and forms prescribed by social convention or by authority.</p>
			<p>Listed below are some suggestions of proper etiquette on the golf course these are some do&rsquo;s and don&rsquo;ts and are only the beginning or basics of &ldquo;how to act when on the golf course&rdquo;<br /> <br /> <strong>DO</strong>:<br /> - Rake the bunkers when playing out of or walking through.<br /> - Be quiet when others are hitting.<br /> - Play with honors, the person with the best score on the previous hole plays tees off first. (Unless otherwise stipulated for a &ldquo;not so formal&rdquo; round of golf)<br /> - Tee off behind the tee markers.<br /> - Replace divots in the fairways.<br /> - Fix ball marks on the greens.</p>
			<p><strong>DO NOT</strong>:<br /> - Run on the green.<br /> - Disrespect the golf course by slamming or throwing clubs.<br /> - Throw pins onto the green.<br /> - Retrieve your ball from the hole with anything other than your hand.<br /> -Drive golf cars inside of ropes or into tall grass or hazards.<br /> <br /> Now some of the things listed above may seem to be normal and some may seem tedious or unnecessary. But this is part of the game. It&rsquo;s what makes golf such a unique game. When you get into the habit of doing these things correctly they will become second nature and you won&rsquo;t think twice about doing them. If you have any questions feel free to call.</p>
