			<h2>Practice</h2>
			<p>One of my students asked me &ldquo;how much should I practice??&rdquo; My response was to say that it varies for each person individually. We all have work, school, family etc. and it is important to make time for those things. However if you want to become a better golfer then you need to make time for practice, your game and your goals. It is up to you how much time you spend on your game but like I always tell students &ldquo;you will get out of you game &hellip;what you put into your game&rdquo;.</p>
			<p>Below is a copy of a practice schedule that I used in college. This was a schedule that I used on non tournament weeks. I had a lighter practice schedule near tournament time as I was usually playing a lot more of the time in those particular weeks. I thought this may give some ideas on how to organize a practice schedule for yourself. I don&rsquo;t recommend copying this one verbatim as it is rather time consuming and designed for my specific needs.</p>
			<p>In general when one is creating a practice schedule they should first plan out how much time they have to work with. As a general rule I believe the average Joe should spend 20% of the time hitting balls and working on their golf swing, 20% of the time practicing on the golf course in &ldquo;real life situations&rdquo; and the last 50% on the scoring portion of their game (Chipping, Pitching and Putting). If you divide your time up strictly by the numbers and stick with it you are guaranteed to improve because your practice is so well rounded.</p>
			<p>As you start to improve then add a twist. Here is how&hellip; figure out exactly what needs to be accomplished meaning what are the topics that need to be addressed in your golf game?? and there for what are you working on in your practice sessions??. Now use this information to make a more personalized practice schedule that fits your golf game as well as your schedule. Get creative for example&hellip; one of my favorite things to do in practice is to play 9 holes from the 100 yard marker trying to get the ball in the hole in the least amount of strokes ensuring that my scoring game is sharp incase my ballstriking is not perfect.</p>
			<p>Good luck and if you have any questions about this article or need any help with your golf game simply contact me and let me know how I can help.</p>
